Gesture-Controlled 3D Puzzle Demo

A minimal demo combining MediaPipe hand-tracking ML with a 3D puzzle game
built in the Ursina engine (pure Python, runs on top of Panda3D).

What it does


Webcam feed is processed by MediaPipe to detect hand landmarks.
A simple rule-based classifier turns landmark positions into gestures:
OPEN_PALM, FIST, POINT_LEFT, POINT_RIGHT, THUMBS_UP.
Gestures are mapped to player actions in a 3D scene: move forward, turn,
jump, stop.
Puzzle goal: push the orange crate onto the blue target tile.


Setup

bashcd gesture_game
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate        # Windows: venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt

Run

Keyboard mode (no webcam needed, good for testing the game logic):

bashpython game.py

Controls: W/A/D to move/turn, Space to jump, S to stop.

Gesture mode (requires a webcam):

bashpython game.py --gestures

A second window will pop up showing your webcam feed with hand landmarks
and the currently detected gesture — useful for calibrating/debugging.
Add --no-preview to hide that window once you trust the recognizer.

Gesture cheat sheet

GestureActionOpen palmMove forwardPoint leftTurn leftPoint rightTurn rightThumbs upJumpFistStop

Notes / next steps


The gesture classifier is rule-based (fast, no training needed) using
finger-extension geometry from MediaPipe landmarks. For a "real" ML
approach, swap classify_gesture() for a small trained classifier
(e.g. an sklearn SVM or tiny PyTorch MLP) on landmark coordinates —
the threading/game-loop architecture stays identical.
push_crate() is a simplified proximity-based push; a physics engine
(e.g. swapping Ursina's collider for a proper rigidbody system) would
make it feel more natural for a fuller game.
Tested architecture: webcam thread is fully decoupled from the Ursina
render loop via GestureState, so frame drops in CV processing never
stall the game's frame rate.
